    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-11-19T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-11-19T12:00:00-05:00" n="808"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d808">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.00/3812: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Third Secretary of Embassy in Spain</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wendelin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-11-19T17:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 19, 1936—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 19—3:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>X–326. Note from Ministry of State dated at Valencia November 13 just received
                    refers to <hi rend="italic">note verbale</hi> of August 20 reported in my
                    telegram No. X–79, August 21, 8 p.m., and requests in confirmation and
                    clarification thereinto that I inform my Government as follows: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Because a zone of war is declared in all Spanish ports of the peninsula,
                            place of sovereignty (<hi rend="italic">Plazas de Soberangu</hi> i. e.
                            Ceuta and Melilla), and the protectorate zone in Morocco, and the
                            colonies of Rio de Janeiro, Ifni and Guinea continental and insular, the
                            Government of the Republic has ordered that no vessel may enter the said
                            ports or territorial waters without its prior authorization. This
                            measure, which it considers indispensable for the most rapid
                            reestablishment of legal normality, includes Spanish as well as foreign
                            vessels, and seeks to protect them, insofar as possible, from the risks
                            which <pb facs="0864" n="765" xml:id="pg_765"/> military operations
                            might cause them, and the responsibility for which the Spanish
                            Government considers itself relieved by these modifications until the
                            end of the war caused by the military revolt.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wendelin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
